Come over - come here

1. Why don't you come over next Sunday to meet him.
%
I am starving - I am very hungry

1. Hungry ? I'm starving.
%
Whatever you say - indicate that you accept what someone has said, even though you do not really them or do not think it is a good idea.

1. We'll go in your car, Billy. --- ' Whatever you say '.
%
It's beyond me - I cannot deal with it.

1. Do you like biology? No. It's beyond me.
%
You are on the right track - you are acting or progressing in a way that is likely to result in success.

1. No, but you are on the right track.
2. Guests are returning in increasing numbers - a sure sign that we are on the right track.
%
You can say that again - strong agreement with what someone has just said; an informal expression.

1. What a tedious job. -- You can say that again !!!
2. You can say that again. Chinese are very concious of what other people think of them.
%
Growing up to do - Become a bit more mature

1. He has a lot of growing up to do. He is very childish.
%
Give it to me straight - speak honestly and frankly to me

1. What a shifty arguer he is, refusing ever to give a straight answer to a straight question.
%
Lay someone off - discharge a worker temporarily or permanently because of a shortage of work.

1. The company has laid off 30 per cent of its staff.
%
I'll tell you what - introduce suggestion or a new topic of conversation

1. I tell you what, I'll bring the water in a separate glass.
2. I'll tell you what -- name the place and I'll pick you up.
%
In a row - happens that number of times without a break

1. We have three holidays in a row.
2. They have won five championships in a row.
%
Up to something - secretly doing smething

1. Why did you need a room unless you were up to something.
2. Hey! I should have known you were up to something.
%
In the air - felt to be present, but it is not talked about

1. There was great excitement in the air.
2. We felt a sense of tension in the air.
3. There's a rumor in the air that they're closing, or Christmas is in the air.
%
Don't flatter yourself - disagree with your good opinion of yourself.

1. I flatter myself that this campaign will put an end to the war.
2. Yeah. She's totally into me. She calls me all the time. Don't flatter yourself!
%
Put off - To hold back to a later time

1. I'll put this project off for a while.
%
Don't get me started - means the person has a tale to tell that will go on and on

1. AOE is a good game. Don't get me started!
%
fall flat on its face - to fail or make a mistake in an embarrassing way

1. Several attempts at humour during his speech fell flat.
2. The jokes fell flat.
